private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(BlobTriggerFunction.class);
This intiliaziae a logger using sl4j -- simple logging facade in java
we need to add logging backend like like logback --

hus logback class is recommended for production envs --> SLF4J automatically binds to Logback if it’s on the classpath.

implementation("ch.qos.logback:logback-classic:1.4.11"). in gradle

<dependency>.       --> in maven
  <groupId>ch.qos.logback</groupId>
  <artifactId>logback-classic</artifactId>. thus lgback class is recommeded for production envs
  <version>1.4.11</version>
</dependency>

You can add a logback.xml file for detailed logging control: like the one below
<configuration>
  <appender name="STDOUT" class="ch.qos.logback.core.ConsoleAppender">
    <encoder><pattern>%d [%thread] %-5level %logger{36} - %msg%n</pattern></encoder>
  </appender>

  <root level="INFO"> -- here we can dcefine what kidn of logging we wuld like
    <appender-ref ref="STDOUT"/>
  </root>
</configuration>

----
to keeps  it consistent throught the application in multimodule project
we can add the version in main pom.xml
<properties>
    <logback.version>1.4.11</logback.version>
</properties>

when we add these logs will actually work in the production - we can configure the log levels as well
trace, error info debug
we should ot have debug in prod envs
never have huge payloads or ids or sensative information
these logs can be then redirected to application Azure App Insights,some external loggings like grafana or some other stuff
also to azure monitor, local terminal

