In a multimoudule project we can have a common module
Logging setup
	•	POJOs (e.g., IdpcMetadata)
	•	Utility classes (e.g., BlobHelper, RetryUtils)
	•	Configuration (e.g., AzureBlobConfig)

basically the modules dont share code
they don’t share runtime code, but they share build-time libraries,
configurations, and utility logic at development time, using a shared common module.

what can be shared in a common modukle
constants common pojos, Utility Classes BlobHelper, RetryUtils, JsonUtil
custom exceptions ,config loaders

These are compiled and packaged into each Function App when you build

Each Azure Function App (module) is independently deployed — they each have their own copy of the compiled shared code from common-utils.jar.
If common-utils changes, all modules that depend on it must rebuild and re-deploy to get the update

Benefits of This Model
	•	✅ DRY principle: Don’t Repeat Yourself
	•	✅ Standardization: Same logging/auth/config practices across all modules
	•	✅ Testability: You can test utilities in isolation
	•	✅ Separation of Concerns: Easier maintenance

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    Azure Function Apps                         │
├─────────────────┬─────────────────┬─────────────────┬───────────┤
│ Metadata Check  │   Ingestion     │ Answer Retrieval│  Scoring  │
│ Function App    │   Function App  │   Function App  │Function App│
├─────────────────┼─────────────────┼─────────────────┼───────────┤
│ • BlobTrigger   │ • QueueTrigger  │ • HttpTrigger   │• QueueTrigger│
│ • Common JAR    │ • Common JAR    │ • Common JAR    │• Common JAR │
│ • Jackson       │ • Jackson       │ • Jackson       │• Jackson   │
│ • SLF4J         │ • SLF4J         │ • SLF4J         │• SLF4J     │
│ • Azure SDK     │ • Azure SDK     │ • Azure SDK     │• Azure SDK │


When you create a configuration class in the common library, here's exactly what happens:

